Tested & Proven in Baja with @hondaoffroadracing

"Racing in Baja can take its toll on our race equipment. That’s why Team Honda chooses to coat and protect all bare steel parts with STEEL-IT: The chassis, front arms, rear arms, tie rods, four links, etc. Any part of the truck that may rust is coated with STEEL-IT. Put simply, STEEL-IT saves us money in labor to clean and scrub off the chassis after every race as well as saving us time to clean up and begin preparing for our next race. We wouldn’t race in Mexico without all bare steel parts coated with STEEL-IT. It is common for teams to powder coat their chassis, however powder coating can hide micro cracks at key points in the chassis, stress fractures may go undiscovered an cause a failure or serious injury.”

- Jeff Proctor, Team Principal

I get a LOT of questions about @steelitcoatings since my ENTIRE Jeep is coated, Here’s a quick rundown…

 I tried several different things to paint my axles and armor, with when I first built myJeep. Powder coat didn’t make any sense because of cost and inability to touch it up easily. Cheap paints had the finish I wanted, but I found myself unhappy with the results I got out of a cheap rattle can. I also used bedliner for a while, and it held up great but after a year or two I just got tired of how it looked. I came across Steel-It and ordered a free sample from them to try on one of the bolt on brackets I had at the time. I followed the instructions to a T and put a lot of time into prep and the results I got had me sold. 

I know everybody has their own results when trying different products like this, but mine were excellent (this is just my personal experience). It’s a big move to paint an entire vehicle and a coating like this, probably not the most practical for your every day jeeper but like most things, nothing about what I built was practical. I didn’t build my jeep to be just like every other TJ out there. I tried to do unique things to stand out as well as maximize the performance I could get out of a jeep the way I was building it and Steel-it fell right in with that pattern. 

It’s unfortunate to see in this industry where a lot of people will bash or hate on a product for having one bad experience especially with something like paint where it requires a lot of prep and proper application to get good results. When someone leaves a review, you don’t know how things were done and what went into their coating process. When people ask me how I apply Steel-It recommend the same thing which follows along thoroughly with their application instructions.

Nothing is perfect by any means, Hell there are parts on my jeep that look far from perfect and I have no problem admitting that.  Being that my ENTIRE jeep is painted in Steel-it should speak for itself with the quality results you can get when you put in the time to apply properly. 

This wasn’t meant to bash any person or company, just sharing my personal experience.
